2.4 Kinetic Energy
The kinetic energy \(T\) of the system of particles is defined to be the sum of their individual kinetic energies: \[\begin{align}
    T = \sum_{k=1}^nT_k = \sum_{k=1}^n\frac{1}{2}m_k\mathbf{v}_k\cdot\mathbf{v}_k.
\end{align}\]
In general, the kinetic energy of the system is not equal to the kinetic energy of the center of mass.
Using the center of mass, \[\begin{align}
    T = \frac{1}{2}m\mathbf{v}_C\cdot\mathbf{v}_C + \frac{1}{2}\sum_{k=1}^nm_k(\mathbf{v}_k-\mathbf{v}_C)\cdot(\mathbf{v}_k-\mathbf{v}_C).
\end{align}\]






