2.7 Work-Energy Theorem
The work-energy theorem and the energy conservation for a system of particles are then \[\begin{align}
    \dot{T} = \sum_{k=1}^n\mathbf{F}_k\cdot\mathbf{v}_k,
\end{align}\] and \[\begin{align}
    \dot{E} = \sum_{k=1}^n\mathbf{F}_{nc_k}\cdot\mathbf{v}_K
\end{align}\] where \(\mathbf{F}_{nc_k}\) is the nonconservative force acting on the \(k\)th particle and \(E\) is the total energy of the system of particles.
Integrating with respect to time, we get \[\begin{align}
    \begin{split}
        T(t_2)-T(t_1) = \sum_{k=1}^n W_{\mathbf{F}_k,12}
    \end{split}
\end{align}\] where the work of force \(\mathbf{F}_k\) is \[\begin{align}
    \begin{split}
        W_{\mathbf{F}_k,12} = \int_{t_1}^{t_2} \mathbf{F}_k\cdot\mathbf{v}_kdt = \int_{\mathbf{r}(t_1)}^{\mathbf{r}(t_2)}\mathbf{F}_k d\mathbf{r}_k.
    \end{split}
\end{align}\]






ImportantNote!



The work of the force is the integral of the force dotted with the velocity of displacement of the point of application of the force.








