This is a nonconservative system.
Moments can also be conservative.
A torsional spring is just a model for some kind of elasticity at the joint.
The torsional spring with stiffness \(K\) creates a couple \[\begin{align}
    \mathbf{M}_S = K\theta(-\mathbf{E}_Z)
\end{align}\] The power of the couple is \[\begin{align}
    \mathbf{M}_S\cdot\boldsymbol{\omega} = -K\theta\dot{\theta} = -\frac{d}{dt}\left( K\frac{\dot{\theta}^2}{2} \right).
\end{align}\] Hence, \(U = \frac{1}{2}K\dot{\theta}^2\) for the torsional spring.
A constant couple \(\mathbf{M}_e = M_e\mathbf{E}_Z\) is also conservative. Its power is \[\begin{align}
    \mathbf{M}_e\cdot\boldsymbol{\omega} = M_e\dot{\theta} = -\frac{d}{dt}(-M_e\theta).
\end{align}\] Hence, \(U = -M_e\theta\) for a constant couple.
Note. This only works for \(\boldsymbol{\omega} = \omega\mathbf{E}_z\). Constant couples are not conservative in general.
